entry.title: [AsyncSB] Inject AsyncCheckTracker into BrowserUrlLoaderThrottle
entry.content:
With async Safe Browsing checks, BrowserUrlLoaderThrottle will create

two UrlCheckers, one for sync local-blocklist check, one for async

real-time check. The async check will not block UrlLoader. If the URL

loader is ready before the async checker is completed, BULT will pass

the ownership of async checker to AsyncCheckTracker.



This CL injects AsyncCheckTracker into BrowserUrlLoaderThrottle.

entry.title: gnrt: Inherit shipped, security, and group flags consistently
entry.content:
The shipped flag and security_critical flags in the README files

are now consistent in defaulting to the group attached to the crate.



If the config specifies shipped/security_critical for the crate

itself or any ancestor of it, that overrides. If a crate is a

top level dependency (used by 1p code) then it is considered as

both shipped and security_critical by default. Otherwise, it uses

the group that is determined for the crate to set the flag. Safe

and Sandbox groups are considered both shipped+security_critical

and the Test group is considered neither.



The group resolution is based on both ancestors and dependencies:

- Ancestors can raise the privilege level. If you're used in a

Safe context, then you must be considered Safe as well. Crates

that don't have a config overriding the group but are top-level

deps of Chromium itself for 1p code default to being Safe.

- Dependencies can lower the privilege level. If you depend on

something that requires sandbox, then you also must require it.

This takes precedence over the ancestors.



`cargo -Zbindeps tree` can be used to view the dependency tree.

entry.title: Fix null reference in PaymentDetails validation
entry.content:
This fixes UBSan errors like the following:

https://luci-milo.appspot.com/ui/inv/build-8763888193215235281/test-results?q=PaymentRequestUpdateWithTest.UpdateWithModifiers&sortby=&groupby=



All the validation methods took a const PaymentItem& total parameter and

did nothing with it. But as references cannot be null, the call sites

called it with *details.total, which is undefined if the pointer is

null.



Looking at the history, the bug was introduced in

https://crrev.com/c/643768. In the old version of the file, the

parameter was const payments::mojom::PaymentItemPtr& total, which *can*

be null since it's a reference to a smart pointer. In the conversion,

this was mistranslated to a non-nullable type:



https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/643768/12/components/payments/content/payment_details_validation.cc

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/643768/12/components/payments/core/payment_details_validation.cc



We just didn't notice because the parameter was unused. The last time

the parameter was used was just before this CL:

https://codereview.chromium.org/2852363002



Bug: 1394755

entry.title: [TrustedVault] Allow concurrent key fetches
entry.content:
This change allows multiple concurrent key fetches for the same security

domain. This won't trigger another request to the server, rather all key

fetches will complete once keys are downloaded (if needed). Note, that

while FetchKeys() could be called for any account, keys downloading is

only supported for the primary account, thus there is still a guarantee

that there is at most one ongoing keys downloading request.



This change is needed to support ChromeOS case: there are two clients

using same StandaloneTrustedVaultBackend (Ash - directly, Lacros -

through Crosapi) and both likely need to fetch keys at the same time.



Bug: 1500258

entry.title: Reland "[ios/uno] Stop migrating most global SelectedTypes prefs"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 1c8eda03211c693548e5e4f32d60ad09c504c5df



Original change's description:

> [ios/uno] Stop migrating most global SelectedTypes prefs

>

> Behavior changes are behind the existing

> kReplaceSyncPromosWithSignInPromos flag.

> Before this CL, the current value of the global prefs was taken into

> account for the new per-account prefs introduced by UNO. The motivation

> was that sync happens to honor the global prefs even for signed-in

> non-syncing users today. "So we'd better not start syncing types

> that were previously disabled".

>

> Well, this behavior is in fact a bug [1]. Pre-UNO, signed-in

> non-syncing users cannot configure most such prefs via any UI.

> Meaning some data types could be disabled without any apparent reason.

> We can even achieve this broken state by:

> - Enabling sync.

> - Disabling some types.

> - Disabling sync (keeps data type prefs).

> - Signing in without syncing.

>

> In this CL the migration logic stops reading the global prefs for most

> types, i.e. leaves the new account-scoped prefs in their default

> states. There is one exception: passwords, which *does* currently

> expose a toggle reading/writing the global pref. So that one needs

> to stay. We also use the occasion to fix a tangentially related bug:

> only the user-configurable pref should be read, not the one from

> enterprise policies.

>

> The main point of this CL is making it easier (in follow-ups) to

> use the account-scoped prefs also on other platforms.

>

> [1] Honoring the managed version of the pref is still important to

> respect the SyncTypesListDisabled policy. That's still guaranteed by

> IsTypeManagedByPolicy().

>

entry.title: [DBSC] Throttle /ListAccounts requests in DICE profiles
entry.content:
/ListAccounts returns an empty list of accounts if the user

session is bound and the short-term cookie is not present. If

such a state is observed by an account reconciler, it will

try to repair it by fetching /OAuthMultiLogin.



This is completely unnecessary as the short-term cookie might

be in the middle of a refresh (as it often happens during

Chrome startup). It's better to defer /ListAccounts request

while a refresh is happening.

entry.title: [enrollment] Split AutoEnrollmentState.
entry.content:
Split AutoEnrollmentState into:

* Result representing final decision of state determination.

* Error representing a failure during state determination.



For now the error is just two states: connection error and server error.

Later the error shall become a complex structure with comprehensive info

of what stage of state determination failed and how.



AutoEnrollmentLegacyErrorConverter is used where the legacy error is

reported. It will be gradually replaces by more informative errors.
